matchdetail.toss_summary: Ireland won the toss and elected to bat.

comments.text:
FOUR! James Cameron-Dow to Hashmatullah Shahidi. Stock ball back of a length, outside off stump on the back foot pulling, well timed in the air under control past deep square leg for 4 runs. That's the moment, joy for Afghanistan! Amazing scenes in Dehradun. 

 Afghanistan have created history by registering their first Test victory, beating Ireland by seven wickets in Dehradun. It looked like it could be a tricky target but Rahmat Shah and Ihsanullah calmed the nerves with a superb 139 run partnership. Rahmat was probably the difference between the two sides over the course of the match, his patient first innings 98 set things up as the hosts built a sizeable lead. Rashid Khan was another standout performer, bowling beautifully on the third day to claim a maiden Test five wicket haul. Ireland will reflect that they didn't score enough first innings runs, despite a swashbuckling fifty from number eleven Tim Murtagh. After winning the toss, 172 was a way below par total on a placid pitch and left them always fighting to stay in the game. Nonetheless, they did themselves proud and showed admirable improvement in the second dig. It's all about Afghanistan now though, back home they will be celebrating from Kabul to Kandahar after an amazing journey to get Test status. In Dehradun the party will go long into the night.

OUT! Run Out. James Cameron-Dow to Mohammad Nabi. Stock ball half volley, middle stump on the front foot sweeping, to fine leg for 1 run, fielded by Murtagh, by Poynter. What is going on? This is ridiculous. Nabi tries to steal a second but it never looked likely. Perhaps he wanted to keep the strike to try and hit the winning runs. Suicidal running in the end. Murtagh did well to fire in the throw but the fault lies entirely with Nabi.

OUT! Stumped. James Cameron-Dow to Rahmat Shah. Stock ball back of a length, outside off stump down the track Slog, missed to wicketkeeper, by Poynter. Rahmat Shah, what have you done? He's been batting so well but aims a filthy swipe to try and finish it and gets beaten by the turn. Poynter has ample time to remove the bails, a consolation wicket for Ireland. A rush of blood from the batsman.
James Cameron-Dow to Rahmat Shah. Stock length ball, middle stump on the front foot defending, to silly mid off for no runs, fielded by Cameron-Dow.

FOUR! James Cameron-Dow to Rahmat Shah. Stock ball back of a length, outside off stump on the back foot driving, well timed past deep extra cover for 4 runs. Crunched into a gap, Afghanistan are now within touching distance of the win.

matchdetail.toss_summary: Victoria won the toss and elected to bat.

comments.text:
OUT! Caught. Scott Boland to Steve O'Keefe. Length ball, working, False Shot to mid wicket, by Dean. Test stars James Pattinson and Peter Siddle have ripped through the New South Wales batsmen this morning to lead Victoria to a 63 run win at Drummoyne Oval. Chasing 166 for victory, NSW were demolished by some hostile bowling from Pattinson who finished with 5-25. Siddle bowled his usual probing line and length and with some assistance from the overhead conditions, took the important wicket of Hughes to get the ball rolling for the visitors. A spirited last wicket partnership of 48 between Nevill and O'Keefe ensured NSW avoided their lowest ever Shield score against Victoria but it was the visitors day who wrapped up a highly entertaining and bowler-friendly match midway through the second session. 
This victory has all but assured Victoria of hosting the final, while NSW will still need to win their last match against Tasmania to ensure they will be their opponents

comments.text: OUT! Caught. Mitchell Marsh to Tim Paine. Length ball, driving, False Shot to cover, by Short. Western Australia have won by 51 runs after a gallant fight from Tasmania. The visitors got off to a great start to Day 4 with the wickets of Jordan Silk and Alex Doolan in the first two overs of the day, however a brilliant middle order partnership between Matthew Wade and Ben McDermott gave Tasmania a slight glimpse of victory. Matthew Wade continued his brilliant form with a score of 134, however, when he and McDermott fell within a few overs, the home sides chances dropped dramatically. Joel Paris and Mitchell Marsh were the pick of the bowlers for the visitors, both finishing with 3 wickets, while Sam Whiteman was named Player of the Match for his consistent batting performance throughout the match. Thank you and goodnight.
